AGILE:
Agile is a software development methodology based on iterative development,where requirements and solutions evolve through collaboration between self-organizing cross-functional teams. 
It emphasizes flexibility,customer collaboration and delivering small,working pieces of software frequently.
Scrum:
Scrum is one of the most widely used Agile frameworks. 
It divides work into time-boxed iterations called Sprints (usually 2-4 weeks),where specific goals are achieved.
Manages the product backlog,ensuring that it is prioritized.
Facilitates the Scrum process,removes obstacles and ensures the team adheres to Scrum principles.
The development group that works on delivering the increments.
Sprint Planning:Defines the work to be done in the upcoming sprint.
Daily Stand-up:A brief meeting (usually 15 minutes) to discuss progress,impediments and next steps.
Sprint Review:A meeting where the team demonstrates the completed increment to stakeholders.
Sprint Retrospective: A meeting where the team reflects on the sprint to improve processes for the next one.
KANBAN:
Kanban Board:A visual representation of the workflow,usually divided into columns such as "To Do," "In Progress," and "Done."Teams move tasks across the board to show progress.
Backlog:Tasks that are pending assignment.
To Do:Tasks that are ready to be picked up.
In Progress:Tasks currently being worked on.
Code Review:Tasks under review by peers.
Done:Tasks that have been completed.
DevOps (Development + Operations)
DevOps merges software development with IT operations throughout the software development lifecycle,covering development,testing and support.
This methodology enhances efficiency,speed and the security of the development and IT operations process.
